content: ### Professional Trajectory I have always had a logical and analytical mindset, and combined with a strong interest in nature, this led me to start my career in renewable energy engineering. My studies did not focus only on technical aspects, but also on business strategy and decision-making. After entering the workforce, I progressed quickly toward roles with higher responsibility, managing projects, teams, and stakeholders across startups and large corporations. These experiences exposed me to complex operational systems and required me to adapt quickly to new environments and constraints. Across these roles, a consistent pattern became clear: I was most effective in dynamic, fast-moving settings where technical understanding, execution, and strategic decision-making had to come together, and where I could take ownership of processes and outcomes rather than work on isolated tasks. ### Motivation for Transition to Data Science After leading teams and delivering increasingly complex engineering projects, I reached a point where the next steps in my career were clear but not motivating. Progression meant broader scope and hierarchy, but the nature of the work itself remained largely the same: execution, coordination, and delivery. At the same time, the learning curve in my day-to-day role began to flatten. I had developed a deep understanding of the technical landscape I was operating in, and new projects increasingly felt like variations of known problems rather than opportunities to think differently. What I was missing was the ability to step back, analyze situations from first principles, and make decisions based on evidence, trade-offs, and expected outcomes. Data science offered that shift. It placed the focus on reasoning before action: understanding why things behave as they do, testing assumptions, and choosing directions based on data rather than precedent. I pursued this transition not as a rejection of engineering, but as a way to move closer to the decision-making layer, where continuous learning and analytical thinking are central to the work itself. ### How Engineering Shapes My Data Science Approach My engineering background has shaped a strongly problem-driven way of thinking. I am used to starting from a concrete problem, identifying constraints and trade-offs, and working toward solutions that hold under real-world conditions. This naturally carries into how I approach data science and machine learning. Because of my training in mathematics, probability, and statistics, I tend to focus not only on model outputs, but on what happens under the hood: the assumptions being made, the behavior of the model under different conditions, and the implications of those choices for decision-making. This allows me to build models with a clear understanding of why a given approach is appropriate, rather than treating modeling as a black box. Engineering also required me to learn complex systems quickly and adapt to new technologies and domains. That experience translates directly into data science, where continuous learning and critical evaluation of methods are essential to building reliable and meaningful solutions. ### What I am working on After completing my data science training, I deliberately chose to reinforce my foundations by becoming a teacher at Le Wagon. Teaching machine learning, data processing, and cloud deployment forced me to deeply understand what is going on under the hood, and what the problem we are trying to solve needs and why. # AIRecruiter  Recruiter-Facing RAG System ### Main description AIRecruiter (this platform) is a recruiter-facing application I built to help recruiters understand my profile more effectively and evaluate my fit for open roles. It demonstrates applied skills in data science, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), prompt engineering, and deploying LLM-powered systems into production. ### Overview I designed AIRecruiter as a decision-support system rather than a traditional rsum screening tool. Instead of relying on keyword matching or heuristic scoring, it uses evidence-based reasoning to evaluate my profile information in context and reflect uncertainty explicitly. It consolidates my professional background, including my transition from energy engineering to data science and machine learning, and it applies evidence-based reasoning to answer questions or assess job fit. The system prioritizes grounded evaluation, conservative judgment, and human-like recruiter reasoning, while still allowing for informed inference about transferable experience and learning potential. ### Problem Motivation Nowadays recruiters face +100 applications through each job offer they post. Current algorithms are mostly based on keyword matching and heuristic scoring systems. The hiring process becomes impersonal, often failing to capture transferable experience, learning and adaptation potential and contextual relevance of past roles. AIRecruiter is built to assist recruiters on getting to know Rafas profile better before-hand and ask any question related to his professional life. ### System Architecture The system follows a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) architecture: Structured profile data stored as curated markdown documents Offline chunking and embedding of profile data Similarity-based retrieval at query time Prompt-driven reasoning over verified context No external knowledge injection about the candidate Two interaction modes are supported: QA mode: answers recruiter questions about the profile Job-fit mode: evaluates alignment with a pasted job description ### Reasoning Design A key design decision was to separate reasoning from scoring. Instead of asking the model to compute a score

external knowledge injection about the candidate Two interaction modes are supported: QA mode: answers recruiter questions about the profile Job-fit mode: evaluates alignment with a pasted job description ### Reasoning Design A key design decision was to separate reasoning from scoring. Instead of asking the model to compute a score directly, the system: Forces structured, step-by-step recruiter reasoning Requires explicit separation between: demonstrated experience adjacent or transferable experience inferred potential Uses epistemic language to reflect uncertainty Derives a fit score only after reasoning is complete This mirrors how human recruiters typically evaluate profiles and reduces brittle or overconfident outputs. ### Tradeoffs and Constraints Several deliberate constraints were introduced: The model may only reason over retrieved, verified profile content Claims must be grounded in evidence Absolute statements are discouraged unless explicitly supported Optimism is allowed, but must be framed as potential rather than fact This creates outputs that are conservative, explainable, and recruiter-realistic, at the cost of sometimes underselling edge-case strengths. ### Technical Stack Python FastAPI for the backend API Streamlit for the recruiter-facing UI OpenAI embeddings and chat models Docker for containerization Google Cloud Run for deployment Google Secret Manager for secure API key handling ### Key Learnings Through this project, I deepened my understanding of: RAG system design Prompt engineering as a form of system control End-to-end development and cloud deployment of ML-powered applications The importance of epistemic humility in automated decision-support tools ### Current Status The system is fully deployed and operational, supporting both recruiter Q&A and job-fit evaluation. The reasoning layer is intentionally frozen to prioritize stability and explainability, with future work focused on UX improvements rather than core logic changes.

### Profile Summary I am a renewable energy engineer turned data scientist, with experience scaling operations, executing end-to-end projects, and leading cross-functional teams in both startups and large corporations. My transition into data science is driven by a desire to work closer to decision-making, optimization, and data-driven systems. I am currently focused on building end-to-end data science and machine learning projects, including deployment, APIs, and cloud-based applications. ### Who am I? (professional context) In my day-to-day work, I value dynamic and collaborative environments where people can work seriously without taking themselves too seriously. I care a lot about team atmosphere and believe that good results come more easily when people enjoy working together. I tend to approach difficult challenges calmly and pragmatically. I learn fast, adapt quickly to new contexts, and usually take ownership of problems until they are resolved. When working in teams, I naturally support others by sharing knowledge, explaining concepts, and helping colleagues move at the same pace, because I strongly believe that performance is a collective outcome rather than an individual one. I have consistently performed best in open environments where scope evolves, uncertainty is present, and problems are not fully predefined. In these contexts, my logical and structured way of thinking helps me find practical solutions across changing roles and responsibilities, rather than within narrowly defined positions. ### Strengths (observed patterns) Strong ability to ramp up quickly in new domains, developed through work across startups and large corporations, multiple countries, and diverse roles Pragmatic, logical problem-solving approach focused on outcomes rather than process for its own sake Systems-level thinking, shaped by experience across technical, operational, and business-facing aspects of projects Comfortable working cross-functionally, coordinating with stakeholders from different backgrounds and priorities ### Weaknesses & constraints I tend to be a perfectionist, which means that in

problem-solving approach focused on outcomes rather than process for its own sake Systems-level thinking, shaped by experience across technical, operational, and business-facing aspects of projects Comfortable working cross-functionally, coordinating with stakeholders from different backgrounds and priorities ### Weaknesses & constraints I tend to be a perfectionist, which means that in some situations I can push for correctness when good enough would already deliver value. Im actively learning to recognize when to freeze work and move on. On tasks that feel low-impact or unmotivating, I can procrastinate slightly, although this has not affected critical deliverables. I manage this by structuring my workload around clear priorities and deadlines. As I am still early in my data science career, there are areas where my experience is developing. That said, my learning speed and consistency have historically allowed me to close gaps quickly when needed. ### Domain expertise: Energy engineering & Renewables I have dedicated approximately 10 years to the energy engineering sector, including 6 years of formal education in energy engineering and 4 years of professional experience. This background has given me a deep, end-to-end understanding of how energy systems and energy markets operate, particularly in renewable energy contexts. My experience covers not only technical aspects of energy systems, but also market dynamics, pricing mechanisms, regulatory environments, and broader industry trends. As a result, I am highly fluent in energy-related concepts, constraints, and trade-offs, and able to reason about both current and emerging trends in the energy sector.
